		<p>A 31 year old man, under investigation for melena, was found at endoscopy to have varicosities at the
site of a duodeno-jejunostomy which had been performed for duodenal atresia when he was three days
old. Angiography revealed an occluded portal vein with an extensive collateral circulation. At
laparotomy some of the collateral vessels were found to pass through the anastomotic site and directly
into the left lobe of the liver. The portal pressure was found to be minimally elevated. Resection of the
anastomotic segment was performed with reconstruction using a Roux en Y jejunal loop. Bleeding from
collateral vessels passing through an anastomosis site in a patient with extrahepatic portal vein
thrombosis has not previously been reported.</p>
